The description of the moustaches is "To speak of Poirot without mentioning his luxuriant moustaches is to commit a grave omission. He was inordinately proud of them, keeping them trimmed and pomaded in a supremely symmetrical manner. His black hair, which nowadays had mostly receded to the sides of his head and was slicked back gracefully, had also once been parted right down the middle. It could be difficult to take my friend seriously when his primness and vanity were manifesting in full force[unicode 8212]however, I had come to realize that he actually preferred to be underestimated, and deemed it a valuable tactical advantage.".






The description of Thomas Hastings is "My firstborn child, already twelve years old. He was growing into a fine young man, though he still had the soft voice and endearing earnestness of a boy, and in recent months he had been particularly eager to take up the 'family business' of detection. I had already identified in him a great potential for managing the finances and operation of our ranch in the Argentine[unicode 8212]before we had decided to sell it after all[unicode 8212]but the keen intellect he was demonstrating in other pursuits had astounded me.".

The description of Grace Hastings is "My eldest daughter Grace was only a year younger than Thomas and was quickly becoming a gracious young lady, as befit her name. She always kept her light brown hair in plaited pigtails. I recalled with deep emotion how her mother used to tie it for her every morning, and could hardly believe that only a few years had passed since then. She now drew great pride and a certain girlish enthusiasm from tying it by herself and generally taking care of her own grooming. On occasion, when Poirot was available, she liked to have him do her hair instead[unicode 8212]he was surprisingly proficient at braiding, having apparently learned by performing the service regularly as a child for his little sister Yvonne. The result was always impeccably even and tidy, to Grace's delight, and Poirot seemed to find the delicate and repetitive work soothing.".

The description of Robert Hastings is "Whereas my eldest son Thomas wholly took after Cinders in appearance, Robert was like a miniature version of myself, from his fair hair and blue eyes to his mild but reactive disposition. Our only major point of difference was his intense fear of horses, developed after an unfortunate accident on the ranch which thankfully caused no other lasting harm. I still dreamt of taking him riding someday and had not yet given up hope.".

The description of Judith Hastings is "The youngest of the family, Judith, was a dark child in looks as well as personality. Secretly I held a special fondness for her, though I did not understand her in the least. She had been the slowest to warm up to Poirot[unicode 8212]then had begun to quibble with him with increasing frequency[unicode 8212]and nowadays they appeared to have reached a sort of amicable understanding. In one another they had found their match in terms of being secretive and obstinate (I will at least admit to the latter tendency in myself)."

The description of Miss Lemon is "Efficient and serious to a fault, Miss Felicity Lemon was Poirot's secretary, loyal to her filing system first and to him second. She had a somewhat plain but pleasantly professional appearance. Poirot had hired her during my absence and had nothing but praise for her performance[unicode 8212]he only bemoaned her lack of imagination or curiosity. I had found an unlikely friend in her and enjoyed her occasional dry wit.".

The description of the housekeeper is "Our housekeeper was Miss Annie Pearson[unicode 8212]no relation to Mrs. Pearson, the landlady Poirot and I had when we took up rooms together after our wartime reunion. Annie was actually a close relative of George, Poirot's distinguished former valet, who now held a very prestigious post on my friend's recommendation. She worked for us part-time, providing a range of general services, and typically went home later in the day to care for her aging mother.".

The description of Bob is "Bob was a lively wire-haired terrier with a mostly white coat and a wonderful temperament. He had formerly belonged to Miss Arundell, a prospective client who had sadly been murdered before Poirot and I ever received her missive. Poirot had been offered the opportunity to keep Bob, but it was ultimately I who stepped in and took over his care[unicode 8212]I have always adored dogs and understand them better than most. His unstintingly cheerful and affectionate presence had been a balm for all of us.".



