Chapter 2 - Poirot Kitchen

The description of the p apron is "I have always known Poirot to be a masterful cook; lately, he had been honing his skills with particular zeal by cooking dinner on most nights, and appeared determined to outdo himself at every opportunity. He was on a mission to render even the most dubious of Belgian dishes somehow palatable to young children. He sometimes spoke fondly of his mother as he explained a recipe's origins, offering us glimpses into a past which he had been reticent about for as long as I have known him.".

The description of the p cabinets is "Poirot's cabinets contained all manner of fine glassware and china, and the pantries held enough ingredients to feed a small army. Everything was sorted impeccably according to Poirot's very particular logic.".

Understand "china", "glassware" and "ingredients" as the p cabinets.

The description of the coffee maker is "A gleaming metallic contraption which Poirot had purchased on special order from an Italian inventor, and which contained a state-of-the-art steamless mechanism. Poirot was a consummate gourmet and often went to great lengths for the sake of his palate. For my part, I have never been very choosey when it comes to coffee[unicode 8212]and in any case I preferred even the bitterest of coffees to the disgustingly thick drinking chocolate which Poirot was fond of[unicode 8212]but I had been pleasantly surprised upon tasting the difference.".


The description of the mixing bowl is "I glanced inside the bowl sitting near Poirot, which was being used to mix some sort of sauce. The appetizing smell made me impatient for dinner.".

