Chapter 3 - Lemon Office



The description of the l desk is "Aside from her [dynamic name of the typewriter], Miss Lemon presently had on her desk a [if Thomas Hastings is morninged][dynamic name of the handbag], a [end if][dynamic name of the shorthand pad], a [dynamic name of the statuette], and some [dynamic name of the zodiac charts]. ".

The description of the filing system is "The minute details of Poirot's every case were stored in Miss Lemon's comprehensive filing system, which is her pride and joy. She happily turned up even on weekends to ensure everything was in order.[paragraph break]Since my return, I had seen Poirot steadily become a lot more selective with his cases. He still delighted in tackling those particularly thorny mysteries which stimulated his 'little grey cells', and maintained a steady income through solving problems for influential or high-paying clients[unicode 8212]on occasion he also acted out of pity, helping a victim whose situation appeared hopeless[unicode 8212]but on the whole he turned down many more cases than he accepted, kept significantly reduced office hours, and more often than not acted purely as a consultant.[paragraph break]Owing to this new state of affairs, Miss Lemon did not have enough work to fill her days (nor enough new material to expand and refine her beloved system), and was growing restless. Poirot and I had encouraged her to seek part-time employment elsewhere, which she had done successfully; having a whole new filing system to elaborate seemed to bring her no end of pleasure.".


The description of the handbag is "Far be it from me to scrutinize a lady's belongings[unicode 8212]still, I could not help but notice that Miss Lemon's handbag was brand new and rather fancy. While Poirot was not stingy with his employees, I wondered if perhaps her second employer sought to seduce her with better pay.".

The description of the shorthand pad is "The shorthand pad was an integral part of Miss Lemon's arsenal, and I had often been impressed by the ease and speed with which she condensed complex instructions into a mere handful of symbols.".

Understand "symbols" and "short" and "handful of symbols" as the shorthand pad.

The description of the statuette is "An elegant carved statuette of a cat which Poirot had brought back as a souvenir of our trip to Egypt. Miss Lemon was terribly fond of cats and owned a few herself[unicode 8212]which is how she came to meet the veterinarian who she now worked for when she was not needed by Poirot. The man had apparently saved the life of one of her kittens and she was extremely fond of him. Designing a system to organize the files of feline patients of various breeds, she told me, was even more satisfying than sorting our own human clients.".

The description of the typewriter is "At one time in my life, I had been employed as a private secretary to a member of Parliament, before moving on to work for Lloyd's of London. I was therefore accustomed to the use of typewriters and considered myself quite proficient. Miss Lemon's mastery of them was on an entirely different level, however, and put my own typing skill to shame.".

Understand "keys" and "typing" as the typewriter.

The description of the sliding wind is "Through the sliding window I could see Poirot's combined dining room and study[if Hercule Poirot is in Poirot Kitchen or Hercule Poirot is in Poirot Bedroom], which were currently empty[else]. Poirot sat at his desk, speaking animatedly on the telephone[end if].".


The description of the zodiac charts is "Miss Lemon prides herself on her encyclopedic knowledge of nearly any subject[unicode 8212]a skill which Poirot has made use of more than once. One of her only weak points, I came to learn, was the intricacies of the mystical and esoteric systems which are not well understood by science. In recent months we had been learning together about mediumship, hypnosis, forms of divination such as the tarot and [italic type]I Ching[roman type], and zodiacs both eastern and western. I found it all endlessly fascinating, though the eerieness of certain practices sometimes unsettled me.".


