Chapter 5 - Hastings Bedroom



The description of the h bed is "Ever since the war, I have suffered from a recurrence of horrific nightmares and unwelcome visions from the trenches. Habituated to my wife's reassuring presence upon waking from these dreams, and being now deprived of it, I had badly struggled to adjust. Poirot was a light sleeper and would check on me when I tossed and turned too violently, which had been an unexpected relief.".


The description of the car guide is "Poirot had pulled out this magazine guide on my birthday only weeks prior to seek my opinion on his top choices before placing an order. He himself had sold his Messaro-Gratz in the previous year for a pretty penny[unicode 8212]in favour of a more practical and less ostentatious vehicle which we both made use of[unicode 8212]and he knew of my own hopes of someday getting back into competitive motoring.[paragraph break]Upon presentation of the guide he had called my attention to the newest supercharged Alta two-seater, excitedly boasting of its one hundred and eighty 'horse-vapours', and I was admittedly awed by the list of specifications. I had insisted it was too extravagant a present but I was privately glad for Poirot's stubbornness, as I had terribly missed the sport and was eager to practise it once more.".


The description of the writing desk is "The desk on which I wrote the better part of this very story, and on which I hope to write many more in the future. In documenting Poirot's cases, I had discovered a hidden passion for the art, and enjoyed it immensely. I sometimes liked to work in my friend's sitting room, in the family flat, or in some [italic type]café[roman type] or another[unicode 8212]but when I needed peace and stillness, I sought refuge here.".


The description of the mementos is "Dozens of mementos and trinkets of all kinds decorated the room[unicode 8212]war medals, souvenirs from places where I had vacationed with Poirot, small presents from the children, keepsakes from our time in the Argentine.".

