The description of the notebook is "I had started keeping notes about the puzzles and solutions of various mysteries in an attempt to gain a better understanding of Poirot's methods[unicode 8212]an initiative which had met with my friend's warm approval. Poirot took relatively few cases nowadays and so my notebook had not seen as much use as I would have liked, but I still enjoyed jotting down thoughts and observations whenever we had investigative discussions.".


The description of the h picture of Cinderella is "Dulcie Hastings, [italic type]née[roman type] Duveen, a professional acrobat whom Poirot and I had met while investigating a case in France. To me she had always been Cinderella, and indeed ours had been a fairytale romance. She had been the sweetest and truest wife a man could have. That she had been snuffed out barely at mid-life was to me the height of unfairness, and there were still times when I would suddenly experience that fearsome rush of grief and anger all over again.[paragraph break]My only comfort was that she died, as she would have wished, with no drawn out suffering from illness or old age. But the deep loneliness created by her passing left me lost and homesick, and in the end[unicode 8212]after arranging her final resting place, in a beautiful and peaceful location which I know she would have approved of[unicode 8212]I made the difficult decision to come back to England.".


