Chapter 8 - Poirot Bedroom



The description of the p bed is "Of a good size and very comfortable, like mine. On occasion I had entered Poirot's room while he was still asleep and found him lying on his back in the very middle of the bed, with his hands up above the bedclothes, looking very much like a great cat contentedly rolling onto his back to show his belly.".

Understand "bedclothes" as the p bed.

The description of Cedric is "A stuffed caiman, brought as a present for Poirot during one of my visits home from South America to conduct business relating to the ranch. I shot the beast on the Orinoco, in Venezuela, and was quite proud of my feat. Poirot, despite his claims to the contrary, was perturbed by the strong chemical smell which had lingered far beyond the time frame given to me by the taxidermist. I had resigned myself to seeing old Cedric relegated to the back of a closet, but had been pleasantly surprised to find him in his place of honour on Poirot's dresser upon my return.".


The description of the family photograph is "One of the first photographs shot with our Kodak, some time after we settled in. It shows Poirot, the children and myself[unicode 8212]along with Bob, who could not sit still and came out slightly blurred[unicode 8212]arranged around my living room with joyous expressions as we posed for the camera. The sight of the great Hercule Poirot in his shirtsleeves, a small child on each knee, never failed to amuse and gladden me!".

The description of the slippers is "Poirot, in his dandyish and self-admiring manner, loved to have his most luxurious personal items inscribed with his elegant monogram of an intertwined H and P. He sometimes wore these dark velvety slippers around the house after his bath, when the day's schedule allowed him to keep a casual presentation. I confess that the aches of advancing middle age were making me crave comforts that I had spurned as a younger man, and I was tempted to procure some slippers of my own.".

