Chapter 10 - Poirot Bathroom

The description of the combs is "Poirot owned a variety of combs and brushes and other grooming tools, which he insisted served distinct and important purposes. He kept spares in different drawers around the flat as if they were emergency kits. At all times he carried on his person at minimum one comb, one miniature mirror and one small tin of pomade, which he liberally employed to set himself to rights whenever his hair or moustaches were the least bit disturbed.".


The description of the p bathtub is "I had initially had doubts about the 'modern' styling of Whitehaven Mansions and its furnishings, as I associated the term with cheap decor and flimsy, insubstantial objects; a far cry from the durable and traditionally charming furniture I had grown accustomed to. I had been happily surprised to find in this flat a reasonable compromise between old-fashioned philosophies and modern enhancements, and the sturdy, elegant bathtub was a shining example of the former. We planned to install a shower-head onto the tub[unicode 8212]I had had the opportunity to shower on several occasions in the past, but never with warm water, and was eagerly looking forward to it.".

The description of the Revivit is "For a few years Poirot's hair had been growing greyer from visit to visit, until suddenly becoming jet-black once again; he had shocked me by revealing[unicode 8212]in his typical jestful and circumspect manner[unicode 8212]that he was now dyeing it. I did not fall in with his particular brand of vanity and was unwilling to resort to these kinds of tricks myself, but my own thinning and greying hair nonetheless distressed me. I felt it was unfair that I should be the only one showing these signs of aging, and looking worse off by way of comparison. I wondered if by making a convincing case I could entice Poirot to abandon the product!".

The description of the p sink is "I have always been too tall to use most sinks without having to stoop terribly; this one was sadly no exception.".

