The description of the artistic materials is "Grace possessed a romantic and artistic temperament, and spent most of her free time practising various crafts. Recently she had taken to knitting, after Miss Lemon generously donated some of her own supplies[if Grace Hastings is in Hastings Dining Room]. Her latest project sat on the dresser, filled with pins marking her progress[end if].".

The description of the chemistry sets is "Judith's uncommonly keen interest in chemistry only seemed to intensify with every new set we gifted her. A few months prior, around Christmas-time, she had come to us requesting more advanced material. I was inclined to accept, having already begun to make peace with my daughter's peculiarities; Poirot, about as old-fashioned as I am but lacking the child-rearing delicacy which my late wife imparted to me, had blundered into a minor confrontation.[paragraph break][italic type]'But Judith, it is not healthy for a young lady to spend so much time with the test tubes! See you, it is important to learn other skills also[unicode 8212]like the cooking, for when you have a husband to feed.'[paragraph break][roman type]When she suggested defiantly that she might not want to marry, Poirot delivered scandalized exhortations[unicode 8212]which fell on deaf ears. Though I could understand my friend's reasoning and did not entirely disagree, it seemed somewhat hypocritical for a confirmed bachelor like himself to be touting the benefits of marriage. I could plainly see that Judith shared my thoughts. With startling suddenness she changed her tack.[italic type][paragraph break]'Then I shall marry a scientist, like Marie Curie did, and we'll hire a cook. Or[unicode 8212]or I'll find a husband who cooks and tidies like you, Uncle Hercule! I only hope he'll do those things as well as you can...'[paragraph break]What a masterful [italic type]coup de grâce[roman type]! I had had to hide my beaming face behind my newspaper. Flattery has always been Poirot's weak point, and Judith was not shy about appealing to his vanity. He inevitably wound up indulging her and never seemed to begrudge her getting the upper hand. That time had been no exception, and I have not heard further complaints regarding the chemistry sets.".

The description of the dolls is "Grace's collection mixed traditional porcelain dolls with modern composition toys. This past Christmas, Poirot and I had gifted her a model that could close her eyes and even cry[unicode 8212]to Poirot's great relief, not loudly enough to be heard from his flat on the upper floor!".

The description of the g beds is "Although Miss Pearson was available and willing to make the beds regularly, I preferred to entrust that task to the children themselves. Becoming a widower had impressed upon me the value of self-sufficiency.".

The description of the g dresser is "On the dresser were tidy piles of [dynamic name of the artistic materials] and boxed [dynamic name of the chemistry sets].".

The description of the g picture of Cinderella is "One of my greatest fears after the loss of my wife was of the girls being left without a female presence in their lives. It had been a great relief to see Grace bond with both Miss Lemon and Miss Pearson, but I could not stop worrying about Judith[unicode 8212]Judith, with her fierce temper, her tendency to keep her own counsel which had so often made me feel slighted, and her complete lack of interest in the usual feminine pursuits. At those times I tried my best to keep Cinderella's words of advice in mind, and carry on her spirit and wisdom. She had shared my concerns about Judith's  intensity of feeling and queerness of character, but insisted that our children should be allowed to make their own choices and mistakes. I tried to trust in our daughter and avoid smothering her at all costs.".

The description of the g supplies is "In terms of schooling and career paths, Judith was by far the most ambitious of the girls. She dreamt of going into science, applying herself to her studies with a focus and determination which went beyond her years.[paragraph break]Grace, on the other hand, was devoted to her artistic hobbies and otherwise did not seem to mind performing any type of labour. She had a marked interest in other cultures and countries and had expressed a desire to travel the world someday. To Poirot's chagrin, her fascination was extended moreso towards the Orient than the Continent, but he valiantly persisted in imparting fragments of his own culture to her and her siblings.".

