The description of the b picture of Cinderella is "One recurring point of concern for my late wife and myself had been Robert's innocence and tenderness of feeling. While Thomas has often shown an admirable placidity and stiff-upper-lip despite his underlying earnestness, his little brother could seldom mask his emotions and consistently failed to develop any real sense of stoicism. I had myself once been a somewhat sensitive child but had quickly grown out of it, and hoped to see Robert do the same. Poirot recurringly offered me dubious compliments alluding to my supposedly transparent and 'beautiful' nature[unicode 8212]even Cinders had traitorously agreed with him at one point[unicode 8212]ridiculous and exaggerated perceptions!".


The description of the b supplies is "Robert made up his mind very early on about a career in the Royal Navy and was already champing at the bit as he waited to come of age. He admired the heroics of my younger days and the active role that I had played in bringing down several fearsome opponents. While it pleased me greatly to be looked up to, I will candidly confess that I did not think myself truly worthy of it. I had once led my men into battle with pride[unicode 8212]and even now could still muster up the requisite courage to face most varieties of danger[unicode 8212]but I had developed a sort of cowardly attitude towards military combat which saddened me deeply. I had secretly been glad to be exempted from the imminent drafts, and the thought of Robert facing similar horrors chilled me to the core.[paragraph break]As for Thomas, he was set to attend Eton just as I had. Poirot was outwardly supportive, but it was plain to me that he was actually very upset by the prospect; I suspected a combination of his mother-hen tendencies and his desire to take Thomas into his personal tutelage. I could hardly condemn his feeling[unicode 8212]the thought of separating the family even temporarily after we had suffered such a devastating loss put a significant damper on my own feelings of excitement and fatherly pride. Besides, the idea of having one of the world's finest minds bent to my son's education and training held a strong appeal. In the end, war broke out before the next school year, which cemented our decision to hold Thomas back after all.".


The description of the ball is "Bob had a habit of keeping his favourite ball in the boys[apostrophe] bedroom. The sight of it called to mind that fateful case in Market Basing which brought him into our care. There had been a theory that the victim fell down the stairs after tripping on a ball which Bob had left nearby[unicode 8212]he had ultimately been cleared, but I still thought it wise to watch my step.".


The description of the familiar book is "[one of]On giving the book a second glance, I quickly recognized it as a[or]A[stopping] copy of [italic type]The Big Four[roman type], written by myself two decades prior. My friend Mrs Oliver[unicode 8212]who is an acclaimed author of detective fiction and has offered positive critique of my accounts of Poirot's cases[unicode 8212]had shocked and saddened me by implying that this book was by far my worst. To me it seemed a faithful retelling of the most exciting and eventful adventure I have ever had with Poirot, and one where I had truly appeared at my best. I had lent Thomas my own personal copy.".


The description of the stuffed rabbit is "Robert's beloved stuffed animal, modeled after Peter Rabbit. It worried me to see him hold onto a toy like this at his age, but I continually reminded myself of Cinderella's advice not to be an overbearing parent, and tried to trust that I was bringing him up adequately enough already.".


The description of the model ships is "Robert's love of little army-men was only outmatched by his passion for ships of all kinds. In the corner of the room was the jewel of his collection[unicode 8212]a magnificient miniature sailboat, with a mast nearly as tall as I am, which Poirot and I had purchased on my sudden fancy to float a ship around park ponds as a summer pastime.  I had sadly not been able to bring it with me to the Argentine and was glad to find that my friend had kept it. The ship was still sometimes taken out for a bit of sailing, but it typically served a more decorative purpose nowadays.".
 

Chapter 9 - Hastings Study


The description of the Monopoly is "A favourite in our household[unicode 8212]each child had a lucky game piece and a preferred strategy. I fared well whenever we all played together but had managed to beat Poirot himself only once, thanks to an improbable string of disastrous dice throws on his part. The fancy-dressed and mustachioed man printed on some of the cards, who bore a striking resemblance to my friend, had been the subject of many jokes among the children[if Hercule Poirot is not in Poirot Kitchen]. At the moment they were enthusiastically playing, treating the purchase and sale of their little properties with the utmost seriousness[end if].".

The description of the games is "Card games such as cribbage and rummy had been so popular with the children that we had sought out other games for them to learn, and had now grown a respectable collection. Some favourites were draughts, chess, Jiggle-Joggle, Ludo, and of course Monopoly[if Hercule Poirot is not in Poirot Kitchen] (which was currently in use)[end if]. Miss Lemon had also recently passed on an old game titled Pank-a-Squith, which had fascinated the girls and reminded me of Cinderella's own support of women's suffrage[unicode 8212]my late wife could be remarkably passionate about these topics despite her otherwise carefree nature.".

The description of the h bookshelf is "In the bookcase was an eclectic mix of children's books[unicode 8212]a more varied and stimulating offer than I had gotten in my own childhood. Some of them were beginning to be outgrown by even the youngest of the family, while others still saw regular use. Among the many titles were [italic type]Alice's Adventures in Wonderland[roman type], [italic type]The Hobbit[roman type], [italic type]Mary Poppins[roman type], [italic type]Nancy Drew[roman type], [italic type]The Tale of Peter Rabbit[roman type], [italic type]Winnie-the-Pooh[roman type], [italic type]Fables de La Fontaine[roman type], [italic type]Contes de ma mère l'Oye[roman type], and [italic type]Pinocchio[roman type] (Poirot, being multi-lingual, had been tempted to acquire it in the original Italian[unicode 8212]but I felt that one foreign language in their education was enough for the time being). Lately my friend had also proudly introduced a few contemporary Belgian comic-books; the children were especially fond of the [italic type]Tintin[roman type] series, which featured a small dog strongly resembling Bob.".

