Abouting is an action applying to nothing. Understand "ABOUT" as abouting.
Report abouting:
	say "[italic type][bracket]There is no way to lose this game[unicode 8212]making mistakes may result in a slightly different path for the story, but will never put an end to it. There is a help guide available (which includes the building's floor plans as well as various hints and tips) on the IFComp site and in the downloadable folder. The bulk of the experience consists of LOOK-ing in rooms and EXAMINE-ing various things, but a small range of other actions can be attempted, most of them only useful or relevant in limited cases.[line break]You will not need more than these actions to reach the end of the story:[line break]- GO [bracket]in a direction[close bracket][line break]- EXAMINE (or X) [bracket]something or someone[close bracket][line break]- TALK TO (or T) [bracket]someone[close bracket][line break]- LOOK (or L) (for a description of the current room)[line break]- WEAR [bracket]something[close bracket][line break]- USE [bracket]something[close bracket][line break]- TAKE [bracket]something[close bracket][line break]- READ [bracket]something[close bracket][line break]You may type COMMANDS for a more complete list of accepted verbs, or HELP for more details regarding movement and interaction within the environment. The status bar at the top of the screen displays your current room and objective.[paragraph break]Nouns highlighted in [bold type]bold[italic type] are generally the more important ones, and can almost always be abbreviated to their first three letters for convenience. Every effort has been made to allow a variety of synonyms and interactions[unicode 8212]however, due to the hand-crafted nature of these lists, possibilities can sometimes slip through the cracks. As an additional note, due to the layout required for interacting with the interface, this story is best experienced on a larger screen such as a computer or a tablet, and may otherwise be a bit cramped. Sincerest apologies for any oddities or inconveniences![line break]The author can be contacted at arthur.hastings@post.com for any and all inquiries, comments or issues.[paragraph break]Special thanks go to these beta-readers, who generously gave of their time for testing and provided invaluable help: Jude, Franzi, Jirushi, legallyagraverobber, and two anonymous testers (display name to be determined).[line break]Additional thanks to these players, who kindly pointed out further issues and gave helpful feedback: Vivienne Dunstan, iaraya, Patrick Mooney, Tabitha, Rovarsson, Mike Russo[paragraph break]Please note that this is not an officially licensed work[unicode 8212]it is a noncommercial transformative piece intended to fall under fair use and/or fair dealing. There are some direct quotes from the source material, which are identified as such and are mostly constrained to two specific items; they were copied from Project Gutenberg in the U.S. public domain. All credit otherwise goes to Agatha Christie, to the copyright holders, and to the people who did the phenomenal work of translating Christie's masterful prose into official adaptations (with special mention to the television series [roman type]Agatha Christie's Poirot[italic type]).[line break]A list of sources, attributions, references and inspirations can be found at thelittlefour.blog .[close bracket][roman type][line break]".

Helping is an action applying to nothing. Understand "HELP", "H", "HINT", "HINTS", "INSTRUCTION", "direction", "directions" and "INSTRUCTIONS" as helping.

Report helping:
	say "[italic type][bracket]In this type of interactive story, a text parser is used to interact with your environment. You do not need to worry about winning or losing[unicode 8212]the narrative will continue to unfold regardless, only changing in small ways to respond to your choices. The story should normally proceed fairly smoothly, but if you feel stuck at any point, there is a help guide (which includes the building's floor plans) available on the IFComp site and in the downloadable folder.
[line break][line break]The parser accepts simple commands which are typically composed of one verb and, when relevant, one noun.[line break]Common synonyms for nouns are usually accepted. Terms made up of multiple words can be abbreviated to a single word. Articles are optional[unicode 8212]you can PET THE DOG or simply PET DOG. Uppercase letters are used here for ease of reading, but inputs are not case-sensitive.
[line break][line break]To move around, you can GO in any cardinal direction (NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, WEST) as well as UP and DOWN or INSIDE and OUTSIDE. Example: you can move northward by typing GO NORTH
[line break][line break]The parser is designed to understand directions even without the use of GO, and every direction can also be abbreviated to a single initial letter (save for IN/OUT) for convenience's sake. Example: you can move southward by typing SOUTH or S[paragraph break]At any time, you can input LOOK (or L) to view the description of the room you are in. The status bar at the top of the screen will display some basic information about the current story state. Some other useful commands are EXAMINE (or X), TALK TO (or T), READ (or R), OPEN and CLOSE, INVENTORY (or I), and TAKE.[paragraph break]Examples of valid inputs with varying degrees of abbreviation: EXAMINE MYSELF, T POIROT (for talking to Poirot), R BOOK (for reading a book), OPEN DRA (for opening a drawer), X REF (for examining the refrigerator), L (for printing a new description of the current room).[paragraph break]The commands SAVE and RESTORE can be used to mark your progress; however, if you are playing directly on the IFComp website instead of playing a downloaded copy, please be warned that updates to the entry (for necessary bug fixes, etc.) may occur between different visits, which will unfortunately make the old save files incompatible. You are very welcome to contact the author at arthur.hastings@post.com if you need technical assistance or have any other questions.
[line break][line break]For more information about this particular work and the actions that are most relevant to it, you may use the ABOUT command. For a more complete list of available actions, type COMMANDS.[close bracket][roman type][line break]".


