Understand the command "make" as "take".


Before thinking:
	say "I tried to appeal to my little grey cells, but they did not offer me much insight." instead.


Commanding is an action applying to nothing. Understand "commands", "COMMAND", "verb" and "VERBS" as commanding.
Carry out commanding:
	say "[italic type][bracket]Here are most of the commands accepted by this game's parser; a majority are default commands of the Inform 7 system which have been repurposed for this story's context.[paragraph break]Note: Some actions have multiple synonymous commands (for example, the commands WEAR and DON both result in the same action), but only one option is listed for each. Many of these actions do not serve to advance the main events of the narrative and exist purely for creating atmosphere and entertainment (oftentimes resulting in an in-character 'failure' message).[paragraph break]Commands which have a story effect, listed roughly in order of their usefulness for advancing the central narrative and/or the number of different responses they can give:[line break]GO (in a direction), EXAMINE, LOOK (or L), TALK TO (or T), READ, DON and DOFF, TAKE and DROP, INVENTORY (or I), OPEN and CLOSE, EAT and DRINK, USE, KISS, SMELL, TASTE, TOUCH, PET, SWITCH (ON / OFF), LISTEN, THINK, WAVE, JUMP, WAIT, YES and NO (meant to be used when answering direct questions).[line break]There are also a handful of minor hidden commands which were added in purely for flavour and to catch some of the actions commonly attempted by players.[paragraph break]Meta-commands which provide a utility external to the story and exist only for the reader's convenience:[line break]SAVE and RESTORE, TRANSCRIPT (ON / OFF), RESTART, QUIT, VERSION, VERIFY, * (put an asterisk at the beginning of an input to mark it as a comment[unicode 8212]helpful if you are saving a transcript of your gameplay and wish to leave annotations).[line break]The UNDO command is also enabled, but may not work consistently due to technical problems[unicode 8212]a solution for this is still in the works, though thankfully it should never be necessary to undo actions in the course of this story.[paragraph break]Tip: If your keyboard has an 'up' arrow key, you can press it to fetch prior commands you have sent (helpful for quickly repeating the same command). The command AGAIN (or G) can also be used to repeat the most recent action.[close bracket][roman type][line break]".
	


Before taking the necktie:
	if the player is wearing the necktie:
		say "I began to unfasten my necktie, then thought better of it.";
		now the necktie is crooked instead.

Before dropping the necktie:
	if the player is wearing the necktie:
		say "I began to unfasten my necktie, then thought better of it.";
		now the necktie is crooked instead.

