[line break]     I suggested several more activities, but he appeared determined to shoot down every last one. Beginning to suspect that he merely wanted to spend time with Poirot and myself, I relented and led the way out of our flat.[line break][line break]          >>>[command prompt]";
		wait for any key;
		now Thomas Hastings is in the Floor 2 Hall;
		now Miss Lemon is in the Park;
		now the handbag is in the Park;
		now the player is in the Floor 2 Hall instead;
	otherwise:
		continue the action.
		

A thing can be examined or unexamined. A thing is usually unexamined.
A thing can be nailed or unnailed. A thing is usually nailed.
A thing can be claimed, semi-claimed, or unclaimed. A thing is usually unclaimed.
A thing can be memoried or unmemoried. A thing is usually unmemoried.
A thing can be bamboozled, semi-bamboozled or unbamboozled. A thing is usually bamboozled.
A thing can be seen or unseen. A thing is usually unseen.
A thing can be crooked or well-tied. A thing is usually crooked.
A thing can be arthured, herculed or bobbed. A thing is usually herculed.
A thing can be morninged, afternooned or eveninged. A thing is usually morninged.
A thing can be lost, lostish or unlost. A thing is usually unlost.
A thing can be excited, impatient, leashed or satisfied. A thing is usually excited.
A thing can be red, green, paisley or colourless. A thing is usually colourless.

The p toiletries is memoried.

The description of a thing is usually "That was not in my field of view[unicode 8212]or if it was, it did not hold my attention.".

Understand "have [something]" as taking.


Before taking the necktie:
	if the player is wearing the necktie:
		say "I took my necktie in hand, adjusting it.";
		now the necktie is crooked instead;
	if Hercule Poirot is wearing the necktie:
		say "I could see my necktie peeking out of Poirot's breast pocket, but dared not reach for it." instead;
		




Check taking something (called the item):
	if the item is a room:
		say "That was not something I could carry." instead;
	if the item is a person:
		if the item is Bob:
			if Bob is leashed:
				say "I was already holding [dynamic name of Bob]'s leash." instead;
			if Bob is excited:
				now the player is holding the leash;
				now Bob is leashed;
				say "I took the leash from [dynamic name of Bob] and clipped it onto his collar. He snorted excitedly and gave the leash a light tug, but upon being called to heel he sat at my feet obediently." instead;
			if Bob is satisfied:
				say "Bob did not care for being held." instead;
		otherwise:
			if the item is yourself:
				say "I was already self-possessed." instead;
			otherwise:
				say "[the item] would surely not have enjoyed that." instead;
	otherwise:
		if the item is nailed:
			say "No point in encumbering myself with unnecessary items." instead;
		if the item is the coffee maker and the player is not satisfied:
			say "With the help of our marvellous machine, I poured out a cup of espresso, then took a moment to enjoy the simple pleasure of midday quietude. I found myself relishing even the falling rain drops and their calming staccato sounds[unicode 8212]so long as it was the window pane who received them rather than me.[paragraph break]Alas, it was now time to put an end to my contemplation and brave the storm with Bob.";
			now the player is satisfied;
			now the objective is "take Bob for a walk (3/8)" instead;
		if the noun is the coffee maker and the player is satisfied:
			say "Having already had my morning coffee, I held off for now." instead;
		otherwise:
			continue the action.

Definition: a direction (called thataway) is viable if the room 
thataway from the location is a room.

Instead of going nowhere:
	say "This room's exits are [list of viable directions].".
	
To say exit list:
	let place be location;
	repeat with way running through directions:
		let place be the room way from the location;
		if place is a room, say " [way]".
		
Rule for printing the name of a direction (called the way) while constructing the status line:
	choose row with a heading of the way in the Table of Abbreviation;
	say "[shortcut entry]".

